_calibrateMicrophoneKeywords: UMIK-1, UMIK-2, Bluetooth, Headset, Headphones, Wireless, On-Ear, Over-Ear, In-Ear, Buds, Earbuds, AirPods, Eardrops, Air, Cloud, MIDI, Line-in, Audeze, Audio-Technica, Blackwire, Beats, beyerdynamic, Blue Satellite, BlueParrot, Bowers & Wilkins, Caymuller, Bose, Conambo, COOSII, Cowin, Discover, Focal, HD, HEIBAS, HIFIMAN, HyperX, Jabra, JBL, Koss, LEVN, Logitech, Meze, Monolith, NANAMI, Poly Voyager, Porta, Raycon, Sennheiser, Shure, Sony, Soundcore, TOZO, Trucker, Vibe, Yealink
_online2Description:
Welcome! In this experiment you will perform some letter identification tasks and some reading tasks. This experiment requires a computer with at least 6 cores.

This session is the first of a two-session experiment. This session pays $15 per hour. Please keep an eye out for the second session -- it pays $30 per hour. We strongly encourage you to complete both sessions of the experiment!
instructionForBlock:
In this block, you will use your cursor to track the center of a moving black cross until three letters appear, for example: Z R N. The letters will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. They will flash quickly. After the letters disappear, you will report the MIDDLE letter you see (In the example above, the correct answer is "R"). The size of the letters and the spacing between the letters can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letters might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letters with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see in the center?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the triplet appears.

This session is the first of a two-session experiment. This session pays $15 per hour. Please keep an eye out for the second session -- it pays $30 per hour. We strongly encourage you to complete both sessions of the experiment!
instructionForBlock:
In this block, you will use your cursor to track the center of a moving black cross until three letters appear, for example: Z R N. The letters will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. They will flash quickly. After the letters disappear, you will report the MIDDLE letter you see (In the example above, the correct answer is "R"). The size of the letters and the spacing between the letters can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letters might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letters with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see in the center?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the triplet appears.

_authors: Anna Bruns, Helen Hu, Jonathan Winawer, Denis Pelli

The letters will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. They will flash quickly. After the letters disappear, you will report the MIDDLE letter you see (In the example above, the correct answer is "R"). The size of the letters and the spacing between the letters can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letters might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letters with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see in the center?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the triplet appears.

instructionForBlock:
In this block, you will use your cursor to track the center of a moving black cross until three letters appear, for example: Z R N. The letters will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. They will flash quickly. After the letters disappear, you will report the MIDDLE letter you see (In the example above, the correct answer is "R"). The size of the letters and the spacing between the letters can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letters might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letters with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.

questionAndAnswer01: Biomes_1|Biomes are large areas with similar climates, plants, and animals.|What are biomes?|Biomes are specific types of plants found in certain areas.|Biomes study how climate affects living organisms.|Biomes are divisions of the Earth's surface based only on temperature.|Biomes are areas with similar weather but varying plant and animal life.|Biomes are large areas with similar climates, plants, and animals.

questionAndAnswer05: Biomes_5|They have adapted to survive the harsh conditions.|According to the text, how have plants in desert biomes adapted?|They have adapted to survive extreme cold temperatures at night.|They have adapted to survive solely on the moisture in the air.|They have adapted to survive the harsh conditions.|They have developed spines to protect from predators.|They have evolved to grow only at night when temperatures are cooler.

questionAndAnswerQuestion: What features do beavers have to protect them against the cold?
questionAndAnswerCorrectAnswer: A thick layer of fat and thousands of single hairs
questionAndAnswerResponse: A thick layer of fat and thousands of single hairs
Beaver_1: A thick layer of fat and thousands of single hairs
questionAndAnswer01: Beaver_1|A thick layer of fat and thousands of single hairs|What features do beavers have to protect them against the cold?|Large, flat tails that store heat|Waterproof skin and hair|A thick layer of fat and thousands of single hairs|Many layers of thick fur and extra fat on their backs|A layer of insulating blubber
questionAndAnswer02: Beaver_2|More than twenty minutes|How long can beavers stay underwater?|More than twenty minutes|More than thirty minutes|About ten minutes|Around fifteen minutes|Less than five minutes
questionAndAnswer03: Beaver_3|It gnaws on the trunk so the upper and the lower part of the trunk are only connected with each other at a small point, then the wind blows it over.|How does a beaver fell trees?|It finds a sapling near its den and gnaws through the skinniest part it can reach.|It finds a sturdy, dry tree and gnaws through it little by little, returning to it each day until it falls over.|It looks for trees that are no larger in diameter than their body and gnaws through the trunks quickly with razor sharp teeth.|It gnaws on the trunk so the upper and the lower part of the trunk are only connected with each other at a small point, then the wind blows it over.|It finds trees that have been blown over partially, then it gnaws all the way through the weakened trunk and lets gravity do the rest of the work.
questionAndAnswer04: Beaver_4|On a small island|Where is the beaver den built?|Under trees near water sources|On a small island|Underneath the dam|On river banks|Under water with several above ground entrances
questionAndAnswer05: Beaver_5|Twigs are cut off and piled near the den, while thick branches are sorted out and used as wood for building dams.|What does the beaver do with branches and twigs?|Twigs and branches are staked in the ground around the beaver den to protect against predators.|Twigs can be cut and carried on the beavers’ back, but branches have to be dragged by several beavers.|Twigs are cut off and piled near the den, while thick branches are sorted out and used as wood for building dams.|Twigs are buried underground for future use and branches are used to create bridges between dams and lodges.|Twigs and branches stacked in piles several meters away from beaver lodges to trick predators and act as a barrier.

instructionForBlock:
In this session, you will perform tasks on the computer.
In each task, when you answer correctly, you will hear a beep. Click on the "BEEP" button to make sure the computer's audio is on.

In this block, you must keep your cursor at the center of a black cross until a letter appears. While your cursor is at the center of the cross, please keep your eyes on the cross as well. The letter will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. It will flash quickly. After the letter disappear, you will report the letter you see. The size of the letter can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letter might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letter with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the letter appears.

_online2Description:
Welcome! In this experiment you will perform some letter identification tasks and some reading tasks. This experiment requires a computer with at least 6 cores.

This session is the first of a two-session experiment. This session pays $15 per hour. Please keep an eye out for the second session -- it pays $30 per hour. We strongly encourage you to complete both sessions of the experiment!
instructionForBlock:
In this session, you will perform tasks on the computer.
In each task, when you answer correctly, you will hear a beep. Click on the "BEEP" button to make sure the computer's audio is on.

In this block, you must keep your cursor at the center of a black cross until a letter appears. While your cursor is at the center of the cross, please keep your eyes on the cross as well. The letter will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. It will flash quickly. After the letter disappear, you will report the letter you see. The size of the letter can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letter might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letter with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the letter appears.

_online2Description:
Welcome! In this experiment you will perform some letter identification tasks and some reading tasks. This experiment requires a computer with at least 6 cores.

This session is the first of a two-session experiment. This session pays $15 per hour. Please keep an eye out for the second session -- it pays $30 per hour. We strongly encourage you to complete both sessions of the experiment!
instructionForBlock:
In this session, you will perform tasks on the computer.
In each task, when you answer correctly, you will hear a beep. Click on the "BEEP" button to make sure the computer's audio is on.

In this block, you must keep your cursor at the center of a black cross until a letter appears. While your cursor is at the center of the cross, please keep your eyes on the cross as well. The letter will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. It will flash quickly. After the letter disappear, you will report the letter you see. The size of the letter can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letter might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letter with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the letter appears.

This session is the first of a two-session experiment. This session pays $15 per hour. Please keep an eye out for the second session -- it pays $30 per hour. We strongly encourage you to complete both sessions of the experiment!
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the letter appears.

_online2Description:
Welcome! In this experiment you will perform some letter identification tasks and some reading tasks. This experiment requires a computer with at least 6 cores.

This session is the first of a two-session experiment. This session pays $15 per hour. Please keep an eye out for the second session -- it pays $30 per hour. We strongly encourage you to complete both sessions of the experiment!
instructionForBlock:
In this session, you will perform tasks on the computer.
In each task, when you answer correctly, you will hear a beep. Click on the "BEEP" button to make sure the computer's audio is on.

In this block, you must keep your cursor at the center of a black cross until a letter appears. While your cursor is at the center of the cross, please keep your eyes on the cross as well. The letter will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. It will flash quickly. After the letter disappear, you will report the letter you see. The size of the letter can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letter might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letter with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the letter appears.

This session is the first of a two-session experiment. This session pays $15 per hour. Please keep an eye out for the second session -- it pays $30 per hour. We strongly encourage you to complete both sessions of the experiment!
instructionForBlock:
In this session, you will perform tasks on the computer.
In each task, when you answer correctly, you will hear a beep. Click on the "BEEP" button to make sure the computer's audio is on.

In this block, you must keep your cursor at the center of a black cross until a letter appears. While your cursor is at the center of the cross, please keep your eyes on the cross as well. The letter will appear away from the cross, in the corner of your eye. It will flash quickly. After the letter disappear, you will report the letter you see. The size of the letter can vary greatly from trial to trial. In some trials, the letter might be very small. Please try your best to keep your eyes on the cross at the center and view the letter with your side vision.

Click on PROCEED to continue.
instructionForResponse: What letter did you see?
instructionForStimulus: Keep the cursor at the center of the black cross until the letter appears.

_authors: Anna Bruns, Helen Hu, Jonathan Winawer, Denis Pelli
